        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The purpose of hit testing is to determine whether the cursor is over a given object, such as an icon or a button.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Example</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following example creates a plus-shaped region by forming the union of two rectangular regions.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Assume that the variable <ph id="ph1">`point`</ph> holds the location of the most recent click.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The code checks to see whether <ph id="ph1">`point`</ph> is in the plus-shaped region.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>If the point is in the region (a hit), the region is filled with an opaque red brush.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Otherwise, the region is filled with a semitransparent red brush.</source>
